caption.text:
We Give Bad People numerous chances, why can’t we give a good animal a second chance? 🦈💕.
.
.
.
.
Happy #sharkweek . Did you know sharks are probably one of the most misunderstood #marinelife ? Especially when it comes to their dietary habits. Contrary to media and beliefs, sharks will not intentionally kill a human as they are not part of their main diet (for most sharks, smaller fish and invertebrates are). Often times an accidental kill has come from a shark detecting humans splashing and going to investigate, and even then it is only about a dozen of the 300+ shark species thats involved. Unfortunately… Sharks are a valuable part to the marine ecosystem but fishing/hunting of them for meat, internal organs, their skin and fins, has  proven to them a greater fear. Just like we give people chances, animals deserve them too… I’m not saying to love them, but to try and research and understand them. Thanks for coming to my Shark Talk. 
.

caption.text:
Amulek, a rebel-turned-iconic-missionary in the Book of Mormon, introduces himself by saying that before he internalized the gospel of Jesus Christ, he “was called many times and I would not hear; therefore I knew concerning these things, yet I would not know" (Alma 10:6). 

Today, we might attribute that flavor of selective understanding to a "framing error" or "anchoring bias," but simply put, even the very best of us are still prone to blind spots. I want to point out a few cultural ones that have been pressing on my mind lately ♡

After the Protestant Reformation and the European Enlightenment, an ideology gained momentum that sought to substitute the secular alone for the unity of secular and sacred. Reason is increasingly considered to be the basis of all experience, strength, and meaning. This rationalist approach has been helpful in many ways--ways I am super grateful for--but it is still only one subset of human behavior and experience. 

This has created a blind spot that has blocked out some of the most significant aspects of our existence. At some point, some of us began to believe that if we can’t see something easily and clearly, then it doesn’t exist. We lost the ability to see what’s missing. The truth is that what’s missing is often what’s most important.

There is a still, small voice that is trying to reach you. It rarely uses words. But it will guide you, it will tutor you, and it will give you answers to questions you didn't even realize you had. 

Competing voices are constantly screaming for our attention. If you fail to hear the still, small voice over the raucous noise of the world, don't dismiss the reality of its presence. Pray. Study the scriptures. Go to church. Live the commandments. And I testify that you will be given new eyes ♡

看其他人的遊記說要收門票
我當天入園不知道為什麼是免費的 
車子直接開進停車場就可以

雪山配上薰衣草好美呀🙌🏻
門口還有一個薰衣草周邊商品小店可以買些精油跟薰衣草巧克力
整家店都是紫色的 加上薰衣草味道聞起來超香
薰衣草的開花季節不長
一定要在夏季挑對時間旅遊 
才會看到整片的紫色薰衣草

5965 Boneboro Rd, Mt Hood, OR 97041, United States

caption.text:
美國🇺🇸夏威夷Hawaii歐胡島O’ahu景點
Kualoa古蘭尼牧場
這個牧場是夏威夷非常知名的景點
有非常多活動可以參加
包括騎馬、各大電影場景導覽、開沙灘車等等10幾種活動
我參加的是侏羅紀公園拍攝場地導覽Jurassic Adventure Tour 
要在官網上提早買票 
熱門的活動基本上蠻早就售完
門票加税後大約$137美金/人
當天需要提早45分鐘到現場
整個導覽時間大約2.5小時
導遊開車帶我們看了好幾個拍攝現場
電影裡的畫面都真實呈現在眼前超酷的
導遊很熱心還幫忙遊客拍了很多照片
整個活動我覺得蠻值得 尤其電影迷會超級喜歡🥰

✅ Kualoa Ranch
49-560 Kamehameha Hwy, Kaneohe, HI 96744, United States

順道一提 
在古蘭尼牧場外面有家小吃店Uncle Bobo‘s蠻好吃的
它是一家外帶小店 沒有座位 
餐點價格都不貴
它的Ahi Katsu Bowl鮪魚跟Chicken Katy’s Bowl炸雞排味道都很棒
雖然份量不多 一份吃不太飽🤣
吃飯時間生意很好 要等大概半小時
老闆有時候還會忙到沒空幫你點餐
建議先在官網order再去拿比較省時間

✅Uncle Bobo’s
51-480 Kamehameha Hwy, Kaaawa, HI 96730, United States
